DENGUE - FIJI (08): CORRECTION
******************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Dengue - Fiji (06) 980115005107
Date: Sat, 17 Jan 1998 05:46:28 +1000
From: Tony Stewart <tonys@spc.org.nc>

The Radio Australia transcript posted to ProMED-mail [Dengue - Fiji (06)
980115005107 attributes comments to me that I have not made. At no stage
have I said that the "current mosquito eradication campaign in the country
is not effective". Any comments I have made publicly were general in
nature, along the lines that a spraying campaign is only partially
effective because it has no effect on the larval stages, and in practice
kills only a proportion of the adults. In the face of an epidemic, a
mosquito control program should include a rational use of adulticiding
(spraying) combined with comprehensive source reduction (destruction of
_Aedes_ breeding sites).
The Fiji Government has mounted an extensive progam to do just that. A
round of spraying has been completed in Suva/Nausori (Central) and Lautoka
(West). Spraying is planned for some other towns. Cleanup campaigns aimed
at reducing _Aedes_breeding sites are underway nationally, through
government and non-government sectors. Hospitals and health centres have
implemented standard [dengue fever protocols for triage, outpatient
management and inpatient management, with good results. The Fiji
government is to be commended for its efforts to respond to the present
outbreak.
--
Tony Stewart
Team Leader/Medical Epidemiologist
Pacific Regional Vector Borne Diseases Project
